Oregon Health Authority
Yesterday at 8:00 AM ·

Oregon Health Plan (OHP) members: Did you leave home quickly because of nearby wildfires without grabbing the durable medical equipment (DME), supplies or prescriptions you need? We want you to know that you can get these items replaced.

If you have any trouble replacing things like DME, supplies or prescriptions, your coordinated care organization (CCO) can help. Find your CCO contact information here: http://ow.ly/jprH50BoEAi. If you’re an OHP member with an open card, contact Member Services at: 800-273-0557.

We know these are difficult times and want to help make sure that you have the medicine and medical supplies you need to stay healthy.

For those who live outside of the Tigard area/region and have been affected or displaced/evacuated by wildfires, you can find support through Oregon Food Bank's partner agencies at https://foodfinder.oregonfoodbank.org.

Please share this post to help get the word out to those who need assistance.

Thank you. #Tigard #WeFeedTigard #StiumulateHope

post_text:
El distrito escolar de Tigard-Tualatin está cerrado el viernes 11 de septiembre de 2020
Debido a la cantidad de personal de TTSD que está navegando por los impactos de los incendios en nuestra región junto con la mala calidad del aire en nuestras comunidades escolares, el distrito escolar de Tigard-Tualatin estará cerrado mañana viernes 11 de septiembre de 2020.
En este momento , TTSD planea comenzar el primer día de clases para todos los estudiantes como estaba planeado el lunes 14 de septiembre.
Además del cierre de viernes, todas las actividades programadas del distrito se posponen hasta que mejore la calidad del aire. Los funcionarios del distrito estarán monitoreando el Índice de Calidad del Aire (AQI) para determinar cuándo reanudar las actividades normales.
La distribución de cajas de comida Packed With Pride continuará según lo programado.

El distrito escolar de Tigard-Tualatin está cerrado el viernes 11 de septiembre de 2020

En este momento , TTSD planea comenzar el primer día de clases para todos los estudiantes como estaba planeado el lunes 14 de septiembre.
Además del cierre de viernes, todas las actividades programadas del distrito se posponen hasta que mejore la calidad del aire. Los funcionarios del distrito estarán monitoreando el Índice de Calidad del Aire (AQI) para determinar cuándo reanudar las actividades normales.
La distribución de cajas de comida Packed With Pride continuará según lo programado.

post_text:
Tigard-Tualatin School District closed Friday, September 11, 2020

Due to the number of staff who are navigating the impacts of the fires across our region along with the poor air quality in our school communities, the Tigard-Tualatin School District will be closed tomorrow, Friday, September 11, 2020.

At this time, TTSD plans to start the first day of school for all students online as planned, Monday, September 14.

In addition to Friday’s closure, all district scheduled activities are postponed until air quality improves. District officials will be monitoring the Air Quality Index (AQI) to determine when to resume normal activities.

Packed With Pride food box distribution will continue as scheduled.

shared_text:
Hazelbrook Middle School
September 4 at 8:43 AM ·

Hello Hazelbrook families!
We are preparing for a strong start to our 20-21 school year. Please help us make your child’s first day a success. All enrolled middle school students should have received a new course in their Canvas app on their district issued iPad. We need all students to complete this short course to ensure that they can start school online on September 14th. Sixth graders need to complete this before September 11th to make their 6th grade online orientation and middle school start as stress free as possible. We can’t wait to connect with you this year!

Open the canvas app and have your child begin “2020 Welcome and Be Internet Awesome”. This class will conclude on September 13th.

Troubleshooting Tips:
https://kb.ttsd.k12.or.us/articles/view/366
https://kb.ttsd.k12.or.us/articles/view/61
Help desk: 503-431-4051

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
August 25 at 7:00 PM ·

There are two kinds of tests related to COVID-19.

-- A viral test (also known as a PCR test) tests a sample from your nose to see if there is virus in your body. We rely on PCR test results for confirming and reporting cases of COVID-19 in Oregon.
-- An antibody test tests your blood for signs of past infection. There currently isn't enough evidence to suggest that antibody tests are a reliable indicator that someone has or had COVID-19 (or that they have immunity).

To learn more about the reliability of COVID-19 test results, read OHA’s guide to understanding your test results. You can also learn more at healthoregon.org/covid19testing.

With temperatures expected to rise to 100 this weekend, Safe Kids Washington County - Oregon is trying to get the word out about the dangers of leaving kids in cars during hot days. Please be cautious about your pets as well.

Safe Kid's Message: "On average, every 10 days a child dies from heatstroke in a vehicle. In more than half of these deaths, the caregiver forgot the child was in the car. If you transport children, create a routine to remember to park, look, then lock. To learn more visit https://www.safekids.org/heatstroke

Oregon Health Authority
August 9 at 8:00 AM ·

If you’ve wondered about what the most effective materials are for handmade face coverings, check out the graphic below for guidance.

And don’t forget: Masks, face shields and face coverings are currently required statewide for indoor public spaces (for example, grocery stores, pharmacies, public transit, personal services providers, restaurants, bars, retail stores, and more).

In addition, face coverings are required in outdoor public spaces when physical distancing is not possible. Children age 5 and up are required to wear a face covering. People with a disability or medical condition may request accommodation from the business if they cannot wear one.

Keep up to date at OHA’s mask page: http://ow.ly/YW0850AUsbL

shared_text:
OHA en Español
August 4 at 10:11 AM ·

Durante esta pandemia, pagar la renta o el alquiler ha sido difícil para muchos habitantes de Oregon. Como es el comienzo de un nuevo mes, queremos recordarle que la legislatura y la gobernadora Kate Brown extendieron la prohibición de desalojo hasta el 1 de octubre. También extendieron la fecha para pagar el alquiler hasta el 31 de marzo de 2021.

No puede ser desalojado por no pagar el alquiler, las tarifas o los servicios públicos que vencen entre el 1 de abril y el 30 de septiembre de 2020.

Infórmele a su arrendador por escrito tan pronto como sepa que no puede pagar. Aún tendrá que pagar su renta vencida, pero tiene hasta el 31 de marzo de 2021 para hacerlo.

Para ver si califica para asistencia con el alquiler y servicios públicos, llame al 211 o visite 211info.org.

Durante esta pandemia, pagar la renta o el alquiler ha sido difícil para muchos habitantes de Oregon. Como es el comienzo de un nuevo mes, queremos recordarle que la legislatura y la gobernadora Kate Brown extendieron la prohibición de desalojo hasta el 1 de octubre. También extendieron la fecha para pagar el alquiler hasta el 31 de marzo de 2021.

No puede ser desalojado por no pagar el alquiler, las tarifas o los servicios públicos que vencen entre el 1 de abril y el 30 de septiembre de 2020.

Infórmele a su arrendador por escrito tan pronto como sepa que no puede pagar. Aún tendrá que pagar su renta vencida, pero tiene hasta el 31 de marzo de 2021 para hacerlo.

Para ver si califica para asistencia con el alquiler y servicios públicos, llame al 211 o visite 211info.org.

shared_text:
OHA en Español
August 1 at 12:58 PM ·

Los funcionarios de salud del estado están advirtiendo a las personas que no coman cebollas de Thomson International, Inc., de Bakersfield, California, después de que 76 personas en 13 condados de Oregon se enfermaron con cepas de la bacteria Salmonella. 18 de los casos han sido hospitalizados y ninguno ha muerto.

"Las personas que creen que han tenido diarrea por consumir cebollas rojas tal vez gusten contactar a un proveedor de atención médica," dijo el Dr. Emilio DeBess, D.V.M., epidemiólogo de la Sección de Prevención de Enfermedades Agudas y Transmisibles de la División de Salud Pública de Oregon. "Sin embargo, la mayoría de las personas con salmonelosis se recuperarán sin antibióticos".

Las personas que han comido cebollas rojas, pero no se han enfermado no necesitan buscar o notificar a un proveedor de atención médica.

post_text: Washington County Emergency declaration continues through August 18
shared_text:
Washington County, Oregon is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
July 22 at 7:35 PM ·

Yesterday the Board of Commissioners continued the COVID-19 emergency declaration until August 18.

Washington County entered phase 1 reopening within Governor Kate Brown’s reopening framework on June 1. The governor subsequently linked Washington County’s future progress toward reopening to that of Clackamas and Multnomah counties. Since that time, Washington County has performed poorly on several of the governor’s criteria for remaining in Phase 1.

“We continue to have increased cases as well as increased hospitalization,” said Kathryn Harrington, Chair Washington County OR. “Due to these community results, we are not successfully operating in Phase 1 and we are really working to focus our efforts so that we will be able to get to success in operation in Phase 1 and also be supportive of getting kids back to schools.”

https://www.co.washington.or.us/CAO/emergency-declaration-extended-to-august-18.cfm

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sUA1NwIAK2s

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
July 22 at 7:00 PM ·

Today we released our Weekly Report, noting that the recent COVID-19 resurgence continued during the week July 13-19: http://ow.ly/ohGq50AFFKf Over that week, there were 2,409 new cases of COVID-19, a 26% increase from the previous week. The percentage of tests positive increased again to 6.6% from 6.2%.

Also of note: Large outbreaks in workplaces, long-term care facilities and other settings account for a diminishing proportion of recent cases. However, sporadic cases (cases not traced to another case) are growing. As of last week, 47% of cases in Oregon can’t be traced to a known case. That means the virus is circulating more widely in the community – diffuse and largely undetected.

post_text: Important information about face coverings
shared_text:
Oregon OSHA
July 17 at 5:17 PM ·

We’ve heard there is misinformation about businesses and the mask mandate and statements that were attributed to our office. We want to share the facts with you. Face coverings are required in outdoor public spaces when physical distancing is not possible. Masks, face shields and face coverings are currently required statewide for indoor public spaces. People with a disability or medical condition may request accommodation from the business if they cannot wear a mask, face shield or face covering, and the business should provide such accommodation without putting other individuals at risk – typically, that will involve accommodations other than entry into the space without the required face covering or face shield. For more guidance and information on COVID-19, go to osha.oregon.gov/covid19.
#MaskUpOR
#OregonOSHA

The 436 new confirmed and presumptive cases bring the state total to 14,579. The new COVID-19 cases reported today are in the following counties: Clackamas (19), Coos (2), Crook (5), Curry (1), Deschutes (13), Douglas (3), Hood River (6), Jackson (16), Jefferson (15), Josephine (4), Lake (1), Lane (10), Lincoln (1), Linn (4), Malheur (11), Marion (46), Morrow (8), Multnomah (123), Polk (5), Umatilla (78), Wallowa (1), Wasco (1), Washington (57), Yamhill (6).

Oregon’s 259th COVID-19 death is an 80-year-old man in Marion County who tested positive on July 8 and died on July 17 in his residence. He had underlying conditions.
Oregon’s 260th COVID-19 death is a 62-year-old woman in Multnomah County who tested positive on July 14 and died on July 18, at OHSU. She had underlying conditions.

post_text: Great example of the benefit of wearing a face mask while in public.
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
July 19 at 8:00 AM ·

We continue to learn more about how wearing face coverings help prevent the spread of COVID-19. The growing evidence about face coverings, combined with our rise in cases since reopening show why it’s so critical that Oregonians follow the statewide regulations about face coverings.

Last week, the CDC released more information about a situation in Missouri, where two hair stylists learned they had COVID-19 after they had interacted with 139 clients. An investigation found that none of these clients were known to be infected with COVID-19. The hair stylists and clients wore face coverings, which likely helped prevent the spread of COVID-19.

Please share the social card below with your friends and family. Help us get that word out that wearing a face covering is one of the best ways we can work together to prevent the spread of COVID-19.

Learn more about the investigation at: https://bit.ly/MMWR71420.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
July 11 at 8:00 AM ·

Yesterday we released new modeling on COVID-19 in Oregon: http://ow.ly/PmNn50AvynL The newest modeling shows the continuation of a concerning trend of rapidly spreading COVID-19 throughout Oregon.

Cases are rising fast, and even a 10-percent reduction in the growth of infection would result in significant increases in new cases day after day.

The bottom line is that the disease is spreading more rapidly than expected and underscores the need for Oregonians to do more to flatten the curve of COVID-19. This includes imiting the size of gatherings; maintaining 6 feet of physical distance between people; wearing a face mask; practicing good hand hygiene and staying home if you are sick.

It’s a reminder of how important wearing a face covering, frequent hand washing, physical distancing and staying home when you’re sick continue to be as we work together to stop the spread of the virus.

As you consider your daily activities, here are four questions you can ask yourself to assess how risky the activity is.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
July 7 at 8:01 AM ·

With COVID-19 cases increasing in Oregon over the past several weeks, answering the call from a contact tracer is an important way we can work together to help stop the spread of the virus.

Contact tracers reach out to anyone who may have been exposed to COVID-19 to provide information and support. If you don’t answer calls from phone numbers you don’t recognize, don’t worry, contact tracers will leave a message asking you to call them back.

If you have been exposed to the virus, you will be asked to quarantine for 14 days after you were near someone with COVID-19, even if you don’t feel sick. This is because you can spread the virus, even if you don’t have symptoms.

shared_text:
Governor Kate Brown
June 29 at 2:03 PM ·

Keeping Oregonians safe is my top priority. Over the last month, COVID-19 spread at an alarming rate in both urban and rural counties. That's why I'm requiring face coverings in indoor public places in ALL counties, effective 7/1. We can and must reduce the spread of this disease.

I do not want to have to close down businesses again like other states are now doing. If you want your local shops and restaurants to stay open, then wear a face covering when out in public. It's up to all of us what happens next.

Please keep your 4th of July celebrations small and local. We saw a lot of new COVID-19 cases after Memorial Day weekend. Another spike could put Oregon in a dangerous position of our hospitals being overwhelmed by new cases and hospitalizations within weeks. Be smart, please.

U.S. Food and Drug Administration
June 19 at 1:00 PM ·

Today, FDA advised consumers not to use any hand sanitizer manufactured by Eskbiochem due to the potential presence of methanol, which can be toxic when absorbed through the skin or ingested. Consumers who have been exposed to hand sanitizer containing methanol should seek immediate treatment for potential reversal of toxic effects of methanol poisoning. FDA recommends consumers dispose of these hand sanitizers immediately in appropriate hazardous waste containers. To learn more, visit: https://go.usa.gov/xwp3c

Oregon Health Authority
June 27 at 8:00 AM ·

COVID-19 cases have increased each week for four straight weeks statewide, and it is spreading faster in the community. Our latest projections show we are most likely heading toward the worst-case scenario we projected last week – approximately 900 new infections per day by the end of July: http://ow.ly/f0gf50Ajmtj

The bottom line is that COVID-19 is circulating more widely in Oregon. Oregon can stay safe if we all do our part to keep COVID-19 under control. If we don’t, our latest projections tell us we risk letting the virus spread fast across our state.

Below are some steps you can take to help us slow the spread of COVID-19.

The Caring Closet
April 1 at 11:07 AM ·

The Caring Closet on Tigard High Campus is closed for the summer. However, you can still drop donations off at the shed at the Tigard Grange from 8am-8pm. Please read our guidelines to help keep our volunteers safe. You can find our shed at:
https://www.google.com/search?q=tigard+grange&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en-us&client=safari

•Please only donate freshly washed clothes sizes 5T to adult sizes for teens. We ask that the items are free of holes and stains, and they need to be age appropriate.

•Please hold onto shoes and purses at this time. Brand new, never worn shoes are okay.

•We do not accept used socks or used underwear.

•We do not accept any household items.

•We do not accept baby items such as strollers, car seats and pack n’ plays.

•We do not accept toys or books.

Please help us by sharing this information with our community. To protect our volunteers these donations will be stored until a later date. If the drop site is full, please take your items with you.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
June 24 at 7:13 PM ·

Today, we released our Weekly Report, which showed that during the week of June 15-21, 30,773 people were tested for COVID-19 in Oregon and 3.7 percent of those people had a positive result, up from 3.1 percent during the preceding week: http://ow.ly/TL2250AhatN

For the fourth week in a row, newly reported COVID-19 cases increased over the previous week. During the week of June 15-21, OHA recorded 1,263 new cases of COVID-19 infection, a 40 percent increase from the previous week’s total of 898 new cases.

In addition, 12 Oregonians were reported to have died, compared with 16 deaths in the preceding week.

However, available evidence suggests average severity of illness among reported cases is lower than it was early in the outbreak: Hospitalizations and deaths remain well below their peaks, even after reported cases have been increasing for four weeks, and the percentage of emergency department visits attributable to COVID-19-like symptoms remains below 1 percent.

post_text: Important update for all the drivers out there
shared_text:
Tigard Police Department
June 22 at 4:41 PM ·

REMINDER!

Our photo speed enforcement program goes live on July 1st at two intersections:
• Pacific Highway (99W) & 72nd Avenue
• Pacific Highway (99W) & Hall Boulevard

There have been some rumors in the community that drivers going as little as 1 mph over the speed limit will get a ticket. That is NOT TRUE. Under Oregon law, the threshold for issuing a photo speed citation has to be at least 11 mph over the limit. Tickets can cost you anywhere from $165-$440 depending on how fast you’re going.

Please watch this video to learn more and check out https://www.tigard-or.gov/police/photo_traffic_enforcement.php for all the details. Thank you!

Para obtener más información y datos sobre cada condado, visite: healthoregon.org/coronavirus

June 19 at 12:37 PM ·

We want to keep you informed about COVID-19 in Oregon. Data are provisional and change frequently.

• Samples for 6,344 patients tested positive.
• Samples for 187,345 patients tested negative.

Oregon Health Authority reported 206 new confirmed and presumptive cases of COVID-19 as of 12:01 a.m. today bringing the state total to 6,572.

The new confirmed and presumptive COVID-19 cases reported today are in the following counties: Clackamas (23), Coos (1), Deschutes (3), Douglas (3), Hood River (2), Jefferson (4), Klamath (12), Lane (3), Lincoln (31), Linn (1), Malheur (1), Marion (20), Morrow (5), Multnomah (49), Umatilla (24), Union (6), Wallowa (1), Washington (17).

Oregon’s 188th COVID-19 death is an 84-year-old woman in Marion County who tested positive on June 3 and died June 10, in her residence. She had underlying medical conditions.

For more information, visit healthoregon.org/coronavirus

post_text: Important new information
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
June 18 at 7:00 PM ·

Starting June 24, face coverings will be required in Multnomah, Washington, Clackamas, Hood River, Marion, Polk and Lincoln counties in indoor public spaces.

As Governor Brown shared, we’re going to have to get used to face coverings being part of our daily life if we’re going to be able stay safe and stay open while COVID-19 is still in our communities.

Face coverings, along with frequent handwashing, physical distancing, and staying home when you're sick are still our best strategies to protect ourselves and our communities.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
June 9 at 9:21 AM ·

The things we say, and the way we say them, matter.

When negative stereotypes are spread about entire communities of people, there are very real health consequences – people are less likely to seek medical care and speak openly about things they may be experiencing.

So we want to be clear: COVID-19 does not discriminate. Your race, ethnicity or nationality is not a factor in getting or spreading disease.

In order to successfully fight diseases like COVID-19, we need everyone to feel welcome, heard and safe when seeking medical care.

OHA en Español
June 5 at 2:21 PM ·

ACTUALIZACIÓN: Continuaremos incluyendo los resultados de las pruebas negativas y nuevos casos por condado en nuestros comunicados de prensa de los sábados y domingos y en nuestras páginas de redes sociales.

Nuestro sitio web healthoregon.org/coronavirus, no se actualizará el fin de semana.

###

A partir de este fin de semana, sábado 6 de junio, ya no reportaremos el número de pacientes que resultaron positivo o negativo, ni casos nuevos por condado en nuestros comunicados de prensa de los sábados y domingos ni en nuestras páginas de redes sociales.

Sabemos que la respuesta a COVID-19 requerirá aguante a medida que avanzamos hacia una respuesta estatal estable, por eso estamos ajustando nuestro horario de reportes, para poder mantener nuestra capacidad.

Estas actualizaciones se seguirán publicando de lunes a viernes. Los datos de los fines de semana se incluirán en la actualización de cada lunes. ¡Gracias por su comprensión y paciencia con nosotros!

Oregon Health Authority
June 3 at 9:01 AM ·

As Oregon begins the slow process of reopening, one of public health’s key strategies to stopping the spread of COVID-19 is contact tracing. Contact tracers call people who may have been exposed to someone who has tested positive for COVID-19 to provide them with guidance and support.

If you get a call from a contact tracer working for your local county or tribal health department, we encourage you to answer the call.

You can learn more about who will get a contact tracing call, what happens on a contact tracing call and how your privacy will be protected by visiting our website healthoregon.org/contacttracing (English) or healthoregon.org/rastreodecontacto (Spanish).

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
June 3 at 7:00 PM ·

We know there's a lot of interest in COVID-19 data for Oregon, which is why we wanted to let you know that our Weekly Coronavirus Report now includes COVID-19 outbreaks in workplaces of more than 30 employees with five or more reported cases: http://ow.ly/au4t50zYhC3

The number of cases cited in a workplace outbreak includes cases among employees as well as cases among close contacts of employee cases, such as family members, customers and visitors.

An active outbreak means that fewer than 28 days have passed since the onset of the most recent case. State and local health officials work intensively with workplaces to help them take steps that protect the health and safety of workers and the public.

The identification of an outbreak in a workplace does not mean there's a risk to all the employees there, or to the customers. When an outbreak is reported or discovered, public health officials investigate to determine who has been exposed and notify those persons directly. Such persons are generally quarantined for 14 days following exposure.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
June 2 at 8:01 AM ·

Did you know Oregon Deaf and Hard of Hearing Services has published a page of ASL coronavirus resources? http://ow.ly/Ri7W50zTM4n

The page includes:
• Links to ASL videos about COVID-19
• Communication resources
• Emergency resources (e.g., food, housing)
• Mental health and resources for emotional well-being

More resources for people with disabilities are also available at www.healthoregon.org/coronavirus under “Community Resources for Specific Groups.”

Both sites feature communication cards, including a new one designed to help people who are deaf and hard of hearing communicate about COVID-19 symptoms: http://ow.ly/ISud50zTM4p The card includes graphics about symptoms and duration and is intended for someone who is deaf or hard of hearing to use to communicate when they think it’s most appropriate.

Dirigido a los padres de familia que tengan hijos en el distrito escolar de Hermiston, haciendo un enlace después con Mónica Juárez del Departamento de Salud/ OHA en Español del estado, expondrán el informe oficial: Las Recomendaciones sobre medidas de prevención del COVID-19.

Además, habrá una oportunidad para preguntas al final del programa y usted podrá llamar al teléfono: 1-509-579-0101

Acción Rural Hispana se transmitirá por la estación de Radio La Ley 100.1 FM. El acceso móvil al programa, está disponible llamando al teléfono: 641-741-1016.

Su organización desea participar en esta serie de radio dominical?,favor de comunicarse con: Ana Elisa Wilson; Oregon Rural Action; celular/ trabajo: 541-663-6359; y al correo electrónico: anaelisaw@oregonrural.org

Oregon Health Authority
May 29 at 8:00 AM ·

Although our state is gradually beginning to reopen, it's important to continue following health advice to keep you and your loved ones safe. Stay home if you're sick. Practice physical distancing by staying 6 feet from others. Wash your hands frequently throughout the day and disinfect high-touch areas. Try to avoid touching your face.

These continue to be important actions you can take to stay safe and strong. You should also wear a face covering or mask while you are in public and shared spaces. At work, business owners and managers must make sure you can keep physical distance from your coworkers and support good hygiene if they want to reopen.

We encourage you to visit our Safe + Strong website, which continues to be updated regularly with everyday tips and resources that you can use as we continue to navigate how to address COVID-19 in our communities: https://www.safestrongoregon.org/

Thank you for doing your part to stop the spread of COVID-19 and keep our communities safe.

May 26 at 1:04 PM ·

We want to keep you informed about COVID-19 in Oregon. Data are provisional and change frequently.

• Samples for 3,879 patients tested positive.
• Samples for 111,571 patients tested negative.

The 18 new confirmed cases and 1 new presumptive cases of COVID-19 as of 12:01 a.m. today bringing the state total to 3,967. The new confirmed and presumptive COVID-19 cases reported today are in the following counties: Clackamas (2), Crook (1), Marion (5), Multnomah (7), Washington (3), Yamhill (1).

Notes:
-- Due to data reconciliation, 1 presumptive case in Josephine County had updated information and their case status was changed to not a case to reflect the new information.
-- Due to data reconciliation, 1 case originally reported in the 30–39 age group and 1 case originally reported in the 70–79 age group were determined not to be cases.

The state’s death toll from COVID-19 is unchanged and remains at 148.

For more information, visit healthoregon.org/coronavirus

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
May 23 at 7:00 PM ·

People have asked whether it’s OK to host a small Memorial Day BBQ with close friends. A small backyard barbeque with family and close friends is a great alternative to traveling this holiday weekend.

Just remember: Keep physical distancing of 6 feet or more between anyone who doesn't live together in the same household, and be vigilant about washing your hands. If grandparents are joining, it’s safest for everyone to wear a face covering.

In Multnomah and Washington counties, social gatherings must be limited to 10 people or less. In other parts of the state that are now in Phase 1 of reopening, slightly larger social gatherings of up to 25 people are allowed and still require physical distancing.

Remember: Smaller is safer.

Find more recommendations in the Governor’s Memorial Day Weekend FAQs: http://ow.ly/jdhY50zO00c

OHA en Español
May 22 at 7:38 PM ·

Los alcaldes de 26 comunidades de Oregon se han unido a la gobernadora Kate Brown para pedirles a los habitantes de Oregon que sean buenos vecinos y se queden cerca de casa este fin de semana festivo.

"Los condados en la Fase I trabajaron arduamente para preparar sus sistemas de salud para la reapertura y deben proceder con precaución," dijo Brown. “Este fin de semana del Día de los Caídos, una parrillada en el patio o una pequeña reunión familiar es la mejor manera de mantenerse saludable mientras construimos un Oregon seguro y fuerte. Si desea salir al aire libre, busque un lugar para caminar o andar en bicicleta cerca de su casa. Y, por favor, use cubrebocas cuando esté cerca de otras personas."

post_text: Be safe out there
shared_text:
Tigard Police Department
May 21 at 4:47 PM ·

Drive safely this Memorial Day weekend! Tigard officers are focusing their efforts on traffic safety during the holiday and will be watching for impaired driving. Please #SlowDown, #DriveSober and put the phone down.

If you do plan to drink, please designate a sober driver who is down for the cause. Last weekend an officer pulled over a driver after seeing smoke coming from the passenger side of the vehicle. The driver’s tire was shredded after a collision. Her blood alcohol level registered .18%, over 2x the legal limit. She had just driven her friend home. Fortunately, no one was hurt.

Every 50 minutes, someone dies from alcohol-impaired driving in the U.S.

Please be safe and have a great holiday weekend

post_text: Prevention starts at home
shared_text:
Tualatin Together
May 13 at 3:01 PM ·

Prevention starts at home. Marijuana is legal for adults in Oregon and that makes it more accessible to youth. It also lowers the perception of harm. Legalization does not change the fact that marijuana use impacts brain development in youth. Talk to your teens and preteens about the dangers of drug use and let your children know your expectations for their behavior. To learn more about local statistics and what Tualatin Together, your local prevention partner, is doing, contact us at tualatintogether@gmail.com and follow us on Facebook, https://www.facebook.com/tualatintogether. #preventionhappenshere #talktheyhearyou

post_text: Free food boxes 5:00 to 7:00 pm at Bethlehem House of Bread today
shared_text:
Bethlehem House of Bread
May 12 at 9:43 AM ·

We’re open today (Tuesday) from 5-7 pm. We’re located in Tigard at 9055 SW Locust St. Food boxes are free, and everyone is welcome - no one should go hungry.

The health and safety of our volunteers, pantry guests, and community partners is our priority. Pantry guests are not allowed in the pantry to shop; instead volunteers (wearing gloves and masks) bring sanitized carts with food boxes down to the parking lot. We do our best to accommodate food needs and preferences.

Please share this post - it helps get the word out to those who may not know about BHOB, but require food assistance. Thank you. #Tigard #WeFeedTigard

May 3 at 7:05 PM ·

Por lo que sabemos ahora, el riesgo de que los animales propaguen COVID-19 a las personas se considera bajo. Se han infectado una pequeña cantidad de mascotas, principalmente después de contacto cercano con personas con COVID-19. Solo unos pocos de los animales reportados como positivos tenían síntomas.

Hasta que sepamos más sobre cómo este virus afecta a los animales, recomendamos tratar a las mascotas como otros miembros de su familia humana para protegerlos de una posible infección.

Se han infectado una pequeña cantidad de mascotas, principalmente después de contacto cercano con personas con COVID-19. Solo unos pocos de los animales reportados como positivos tenían síntomas.

Hasta que sepamos más sobre cómo este virus afecta a los animales, recomendamos tratar a las mascotas como otros miembros de su familia humana para protegerlos de una posible infección.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
April 27 at 7:05 PM ·

As we learn more about the virus that causes COVID-19, new information is coming at us fast. Unfortunately, so is misinformation. To combat this, the World Health Organization (WHO) has created a Myth-busters page to address some of the rumors: http://ow.ly/kQoh50zpH4G

They continue to add information as new myths surface. For example, a hot bath will relax you, but no, it won’t help fight the coronavirus. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. And, viruses cannot be spread through 5G mobile networks.

New life continues even in the most challenging conditions. Whether you are newly pregnant or about to deliver, protecting your health and getting the care you need are critical. Prenatal care is important for a healthy pregnancy. If you need to begin prenatal care or if you have had a change in health care coverage, resources are available.

Oregon MothersCare can connect you to pregnancy information, help and services like food, behavioral health, and transportation support: http://ow.ly/i7r850zoQL3 All Oregon MothersCare services are free and available to any pregnant person regardless of income, insurance status, or citizenship status.

We’ve also shared some helpful information about pregnancy and COVID-19 in the below graphic. And you can learn more at the CDC’s website: http://ow.ly/ah3k50zoQL4

shared_text:
TV JAM
March 18 at 3:34 PM ·

Para toda nuestra comunidad que reside en Oregon:
Actualmente el estado de Oregon ofrece cobertura de salud gratuita, llamada el Plan de Salud de Oregon u OHP por sus siglas en inglés y está disponible para niños, adolescentes y adultos—incluyendo familias trabajadoras, mujeres embarazadas, solteros y más—que cumplen con los ingresos entre otro criterio. A demás, recientemente Oregón aprobó una ley que le da OHP para todos los niños menores de 19 años que residan en el estado sin importar su estatus migratorio. Puede obtener ayuda local gratuita para solicitar en su idioma preferido de un socio comunitario de confianza y certificado por OHP, llamando al 833-647-3678.
Nuestra comunidad debe saber que estamos buscando todos los recursos disponibles para ayudarlos. Es por eso que le pedimos que esté al tanto de las próximas publicaciones e información que estaremos trayendo. Próximamente estaremos con representantes de la autoridad de salud de Oregon, para hablar de toda la información importante en español que debe llegar a cada rincón del estado.

#TVJAM #OREGON #ohp #ohpcoversme

Actualmente el estado de Oregon ofrece cobertura de salud gratuita, llamada el Plan de Salud de Oregon u OHP por sus siglas en inglés y está disponible para niños, adolescentes y adultos—incluyendo familias trabajadoras, mujeres embarazadas, solteros y más—que cumplen con los ingresos entre otro criterio. A demás, recientemente Oregón aprobó una ley que le da OHP para todos los niños menores de 19 años que residan en el estado sin importar su estatus migratorio. Puede obtener ayuda local gratuita para solicitar en su idioma preferido de un socio comunitario de confianza y certificado por OHP, llamando al 833-647-3678.
Nuestra comunidad debe saber que estamos buscando todos los recursos disponibles para ayudarlos. Es por eso que le pedimos que esté al tanto de las próximas publicaciones e información que estaremos trayendo. Próximamente estaremos con representantes de la autoridad de salud de Oregon, para hablar de toda la información importante en español que debe llegar a cada rincón del estado.

#TVJAM #OREGON #ohp #ohpcoversme

Queremos mantenerlo informado sobre COVID-19 en Oregon. Recuerde que esta información cambia con frecuencia.

• Las pruebas de 1,910 pacientes resultaron positivo.
• Las pruebas de 37,128 pacientes resultaron negativas.

Los 66 casos nuevos se encuentran en los siguientes condados: Clackamas (7), Deschutes (1), Lane (2), Marion (23), Multnomah (21), Umatilla (1), y Washington (12).

Un caso que fue reportado antes del condado de Klamath se determinó hoy como un caso del estado de Washington, reduciendo el número de casos nuevos de hoy por 1.

La muerte número 73 de COVID-19 en Oregon es un hombre de 64 años del condado de Benton, que resultó positivo el 26 de marzo y murió el 18 de abril en Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center. Él tenía condiciones médicas subyacentes.

La muerte número 74 de COVID-19 en Oregon es un hombre de 68 años del condado de Washington, que resultó positivo el 23 de marzo y murió el 11 de abril en OHSU. Él tenía condiciones médicas subyacentes.

Para obtener más información, visite healthoregon.org/coronavirus

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
April 18 at 7:05 PM ·

Social connections help keep us healthy while we are physically distancing from each other.

To support the mental health needs of Oregonians over 55, we've partnered with Lines For Life's Senior Loneliness Line. Their team of volunteers and staff are specially trained in working with older adults.

They can provide ongoing support, connect callers with resources, or just listen. Your information is completely confidential, and no one will follow up with you unless you request a call.

To get support, call 503-200-1633 or 800-282-7035.

April 15 at 8:05 AM ·

There are currently no medications or treatments that are effective at preventing or treating COVID-19 and many of the home remedies people have tried are dangerous.

We’re urging Oregonians to continue practicing social distancing, frequent handwashing and frequent cleaning of high-touch surfaces. Please avoid self-medicating and consult a healthcare professional for your health needs. If you have questions about poisoning, contact the Poison Center of Oregon Alaska and Guam at 1-800-222-1222.

post_text: COVID-19 case update for April 14
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
April 14 at 1:28 PM ·

We want to keep you informed about COVID-19 in Oregon. Data are provisional and change frequently.

• Samples for 1,633 patients tested positive.
• Samples for 30,730 patients tested negative.

The 50 new cases are in the following counties: Benton (1), Clackamas (3), Deschutes (1), Douglas (3), Jefferson (1), Klamath (1), Lane (1), Marion (9), Multnomah (22), Tillamook (1), Washington (5), and Yamhill (2).

A case previously reported in Columbia County was reclassified to negative based on revised test results, reducing the cumulative statewide total by 1 case.

Oregon’s fifty-fourth COVID-19 death is a 71-year-old man in Multnomah County, who tested positive on April 1, 2020, and died on April 12, 2020 at Legacy Mount Hood. He had underlying conditions.

Oregon’s fifty-fifth COVID-19 death is an 88-year-old woman in Benton County, who tested positive on April 11, 2020, and died on April 13, 2020 at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center. She had underlying conditions.

For more information, visit healthoregon.org/coronavirus

post_text: Update with some helpful information
shared_text:
CONTENT.GOVDELIVERY.COM
Oregon COVID-19 infections projected to remain level into May, stay within current hospital capacity, if Oregonians continue social distancing

Oregon Health Authority
April 11 at 2:16 PM ·

Here's the latest: By following Governor Brown’s stay at home executive orders, Oregonians are preventing a surge in new infections that could overwhelm hospital beds if left unchecked.

New projections from health researchers estimate that Oregon’s “aggressive” social distancing measures have prevented as many as 18,000 cases of COVID-19 and 500 hospitalizations. However these restrictions must be maintained into May to prevent new cases from rising above current daily levels of active coronavirus cases.

Learn more at http://ow.ly/YgE850zbMGg

post_text: Good reminder for the holiday weekend
shared_text:
TIGARD-OR.GOV
Parks and Trails

City of Tigard Government
April 11 at 7:00 AM ·

When getting outdoors this weekend, remember these tips to keep safe from COVID-19:
🏠 Stay close to home, except for essential trips.
👨‍👩‍👦 Stick with your household contacts.
↔️ Keep at least 6 feet of physical distance from anyone who is not part of your household.
😷 Wear a face covering or a mask when you cannot maintain 6 feet of physical distance - but know that a mask is not a free pass to socialize with people who are not household contacts.

H/T: Multnomah County Health Department

post_text: Important new information from the Oregon Health Authority about those most at risk.
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
April 10 at 8:05 AM ·

Although we continue to learn new things about COVID-19, the CDC currently believes people with asthma may be at higher risk of serious illness from COVID-19.

COVID-19 can affect your respiratory tract (nose, throat, lungs), cause an asthma attack, and possibly lead to pneumonia and acute respiratory disease. If you have asthma, here are steps you can take to protect your health.
--
Aunque seguimos aprendiendo cosas nuevas sobre el COVID-19, los CDC creen que las personas con asma pueden tener un riesgo mayor de enfermedad grave debido a COVID-19.

COVID-19 puede afectar su tracto respiratorio (nariz, garganta, pulmones), causar un ataque de asma y posiblemente provocar neumonía y enfermedad respiratoria aguda. Si tiene asma, estos son los pasos que puede seguir para proteger su salud.

post_text: New guidance from the CDC about cloth face masks.
shared_text:
CDC
April 5 at 11:36 AM ·

The virus that causes COVID-19 can spread from a person before they have symptoms. Take action to slow the spread by wearing a cloth face covering in public spaces, keeping at least 6 feet of physical distance, and frequently washing your hands.
A cloth face covering can be made from items around your home, such as a scarf or cloth napkin. Make sure the covering reaches above your nose and below your chin.
Have questions? See: https://bit.ly/34cFym6

post_text: New update from the Oregon Health Authority with some encouraging news.
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
April 2 at 7:10 PM ·

We know COVID-19 has brought painful disruption and distress to the lives of many Oregonians. But if we stay vigilant, this can work: Updated projections from health researchers show that there is “strong evidence that measures currently in place in Oregon are reducing transmission,” according to the latest models.

The most recent data suggest that current social distancing measures could cut transmission rates between 50%-70% if Oregonians maintain these limitations on virus-spreading interactions into early May.

If Oregonians can maintain current social distancing efforts and the current projections hold true, the state could meet the likely demand for hospital beds under current strategies.

post_text: Important guidelines for Caring Closet clothing drop-offs.
shared_text:
The Caring Closet
April 1 at 11:07 AM ·

The Caring Closet on Tigard High Campus is closed for the summer. However, you can still drop donations off at the shed at the Tigard Grange from 8am-8pm. Please read our guidelines to help keep our volunteers safe. You can find our shed at:
https://www.google.com/search?q=tigard+grange&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en-us&client=safari

•Please only donate freshly washed clothes sizes 5T to adult sizes for teens. We ask that the items are free of holes and stains, and they need to be age appropriate.

•Please hold onto shoes and purses at this time. Brand new, never worn shoes are okay.

•We do not accept used socks or used underwear.

•We do not accept any household items.

•We do not accept baby items such as strollers, car seats and pack n’ plays.

•We do not accept toys or books.

Please help us by sharing this information with our community. To protect our volunteers these donations will be stored until a later date. If the drop site is full, please take your items with you.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
March 31 at 1:34 PM ·

We want to keep you informed about COVID-19 in Oregon. Data are provisional and change frequently.

• Samples for 690 patients tested positive.
• Samples for 13,136 patients tested negative.

The 84 new cases are in these counties: Benton (3), Clackamas (10), Douglas (1), Hood River (1), Jackson (1), Klamath (1), Lane (4), Lincoln (1), Linn (1), Malheur (1), Marion (18), Multnomah (16), Polk (3), Umatilla (1), Wallowa (1), Wasco (2), Washington (18), and Yamhill (2).

Oregon’s seventeenth COVID-19 death is a 90-year-old man in Yamhill County, who tested positive on March 25, 2020, and died on March 29, 2020 at Providence Newberg Medical Center. He had underlying medical conditions.

Oregon’s eighteenth COVID-19 death is an 88-year-old woman in Benton County, who tested positive on March 26, 2020, and died March 30, 2020 at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center in Corvallis. She had underlying medical conditions.

For more, visit healthoregon.org/coronavirus

shared_text:
Tualatin Valley Fire and Rescue
March 27 at 9:40 AM ·

The number of new COVID-19 cases continues to grow here in Oregon and all across the U.S. This is unsettling for what lies ahead, especially when it comes to hospital capacities, limited supplies like lifesaving ventilators, and overwhelmed healthcare professionals. We need everyone to help slow the spread and flatten the curve - by simply staying home.

From all of us at TVF&R, we want to thank all of the incredible healthcare professionals who work tirelessly to care for COVID-19 patients and their many other patients who need them. You are our heroes.

#HealthcareHeroes

text:
Tualatin Valley Fire and Rescue
March 27 at 9:40 AM ·

The number of new COVID-19 cases continues to grow here in Oregon and all across the U.S. This is unsettling for what lies ahead, especially when it comes to hospital capacities, limited supplies like lifesaving ventilators, and overwhelmed healthcare professionals. We need everyone to help slow the spread and flatten the curve - by simply staying home.

From all of us at TVF&R, we want to thank all of the incredible healthcare professionals who work tirelessly to care for COVID-19 patients and their many other patients who need them. You are our heroes.

#HealthcareHeroes
#WeAreAllInThisTogether
#StayHomeSaveLives
#SixFeetApart
#COVID19

post_text: How do you know if you are sick?
shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
March 26 at 8:05 AM ·

Are you unsure of the symptoms of COVID-19 and what you should do if you’re sick?

About 80 percent of people who have COVID-19 will have mild to moderate flu-like symptoms, like a fever and cough. If you're very ill or have trouble breathing, those are important reasons to be seen by a health care provider.

Check out #StayHomeSaveLives social card for guidance on what to do if you’re sick.
--
¿Se siente inseguro de los síntomas del COVID-19 y qué debe hacer si está enfermo?

Alrededor del 80 por ciento de las personas que tienen COVID-19 tendrán síntomas leves o síntomas moderados similares a la gripe, como fiebre y tos. Si está demasiado enfermo o tiene dificultad para respirar, esas son razones importantes para que un proveedor de atención médica lo atienda.

Esta tarjeta social #StayHomeSaveLives le brinda orientación sobre qué hacer si está enfermo.

shared_text:
Oregon Health Authority
March 24 at 12:21 PM ·

We want to keep you informed about COVID-19 in Oregon. Data are provisional and change frequently.
• Samples for 209 patients tested positive.
• Samples for 4,350 patients tested negative.

The 18 new cases are in the following counties: Clackamas (3), Clatsop (1), Jackson (1), Marion (2), Multnomah (4), and Washington (7).

COVID-19 has also claimed 3 more lives in Oregon, raising the state’s death toll from 5 to 8.

Oregon’s sixth COVID-19 death is a 78-year-old man in Clackamas County, who tested positive on 3/15/2020, and died 3/22/2020 at Kaiser Sunnyside Medical Center. He had underlying medical conditions.

Oregon’s seventh COVID-19 death is a 62-year-old man in Multnomah County, who tested positive on 3/16/2020, and died 3/23/2020 at the Portland VA Medical Center. He had underlying medical conditions.

Oregon’s eighth COVID-19 death is a 90-year-old woman in Washington County, who tested positive on 3/19/2020, and died 3/23/2020 at Providence St. Vincent Medical Center. She had underlying medical conditions.

For more information, visit healthoregon.org/coronavirus

shared_text:
Ben Bowman
March 17 at 12:04 PM ·

Now accepting donations! Click this link to help us provide food and books to vulnerable kids and families during the school closure: https://packed-with-pride-tigard-tualatin.square.site

Packed with Pride is a joint effort of The Foundation for Tigard Tualatin Schools, TTEA, the Tigard-Tualatin Student Union, and TTSD Schools Board Chair Maureen Wolf and I. We are coordinating with local churches and service providers, too. We‘ve had 400 people sign up to help in just a couple days, we have contribution commitments over $4,000 in about 24 hours, and we have secured over 1,500 books to send home in food boxes for kids. Unreal. I’m feeling hopeful and inspired watching everyone come together to pull this off.

Proud to be working with Scott, Margie, Maureen, Matthew, Kavi and many others on this. ❤️

Oregon Health Authority
March 7 at 10:08 AM ·

Today we're announcing four new presumptive positive cases of COVID-19 among residents in Jackson, Klamath and Washington counties.

State and local health officials are moving quickly to contact people who may have been in close contact with the individuals who tested as presumptively positive cases. Three of the new cases are travel-related; one was a contact of a known case.

The Oregon State Public Health Laboratory tested 42 samples from 22 people yesterday (March 6, 2020), yielding the 4 presumptive positive cases and 18 negatives.

shared_text:
The Foundation for Tigard Tualatin Schools
February 19 at 12:51 PM ·

Day one of our Phone Outreach was a fun one! We love our student and adult volunteers and we love that our community answers the call to support education!

Night #2 starts in a few hours, so be ready to take the call and get your donation on the books!

Our goal is to raise $75,000 during this Fund Drive, which will put us on track to give schools $10,000 School Grants in 2020/2021 to fund more teachers at every school. We are confident that our community will ASPIRE HIGHER and join us in bringing more teachers and more learning to our kids!

Thank you for your support Tigard and Tualatin!

post_text: Thank you Kim Thoren for making the Caring Closet a wonderful place to volunteer and donate to. We appreciate you!
shared_text:
The Caring Closet
February 4 at 11:47 AM ·

I wanted to give a special thank you to our fabulous Facebook community. I recently passed my one-year anniversary of managing the Caring Closet, and it has been so fulfilling. I am looking forward to continuing to serve our families in the years to come. Our 30 volunteers really make it all happen, and I am so grateful for them. They put in hours of hard work to keep our clothes organized and our store ready for appointments. Your donations help us to replenish our inventory; so thank you for your continued support. I also want to express our gratitude for the amazing support we receive from the Tigard-Tualatin School District and our community partners. Thank you from all of us at the Caring Closet!

post_text: "Reviewing Oregon's recently released public high school graduation rates gives us so much to celebrate," said TTSD Superintendent Dr. Sue Rieke-Smith. "It is a testament to the dedication of talented educators across the state who are committed to student success. As we continue to increase the number of students graduating on-time here at Tigard-Tualatin, our focus is and will continue to be on working in community to eliminate the achievement gap in total. Over the past two years, 7% of students represented in the "gap" are now proudly graduating. Our work is far from done. We will stay focused and continue to push until all TTSD students graduate prepared for their next chapter." http://ow.ly/aiOc50y5ZPk

In 2019 law librarians from the Washington County Law Library helped 65 people at the Tigard Library with their law-related questions. Popular subjects in 2019 included wills & estates, family law & landlord tenant law. Although the law librarians can not provide legal advice, they can help connect people with legal resources. They will next visit Tigard this Thursday, Jan. 9 3-7 p.m. (Image description: man and woman consulting with woman at table.)

post_text: "Families are incredibly important to the work we do at Twality. Our PSO shows up to support our teachers by providing meals and fundraising for special projects and events. Our families show up to our events and are engaged in the work of connecting with students. Without parent volunteers, we would not be able to run our picture days and back to school business days effectively. They support us and give us feedback and they are essential to the important work we do to help students learn, grow, and thrive." Twality Middle School

shared_text:
Tualatin Together
October 29, 2019 at 8:31 AM ·

E-cigarettes and vaping products such as Juul are the most commonly used tobacco product among Oregon youth. These products contain nicotine, which is highly addictive. Between 2017 and 2019, vaping product use among Oregon 11th graders increased nearly 80%, from 13% to 23%. Flavored products are especially popular among youth.

Schools, health care providers, and other organizations that work directly with youth have already been dealing with the challenge of youth vaping. With the temporary ban on flavored vape products, OHA is providing the following resources to help young people recognize the harms of vaping and get support to quit.

This is Quitting — the help and support you need to quit tobacco vape is just a text away. Text DITCHJUUL to 88709.
The Oregon Quit Line has special resources for youth. They can help you quit
tobacco and marijuana vape.
• English: 1-800-QUIT-NOW (1-800-784-8669) or quitnow.net/oregon
• Español: 1-855-DEJELO-YA (1-855-335-35692) or quitnow.net/oregonsp

#RedRibbonWeek2019 #GetTheFacts

"Repurposed Wood Studio makes hand carved utensils and art pieces from cast off wood. Various styles of rolling pins, spoons, rice paddles, wok stirs, cheese boards, bowls, scoops, and wall and table art attempt to find the natural life inside the rough wood exteriors. Often the wood is encouraged to "move" - reform itself after carving to its own unique expression."
Check out Repurposed Wood Studio at Art in the Burbs 2019 -- Art in the Burbs is Saturday, October 12th from 10am-6pm and Sunday, October 13th from 10am-5pm at Tualatin High School. https://artintheburbs.org/2019-juried-artists/

post_text: Wow! We are so fortunate to have such thoughtful young people in our community. Thank you for supporting the Caring Closet. We are so grateful!
shared_text:
The Caring Closet
September 23, 2019 at 10:13 AM ·

This lovely young lady is amazing! Her Girl Scout Silver Award project brought in approximately 1000 toothbrushes, 75 full size tubes of toothpaste, 50 deodorants, 40 full size bottles of shampoo and conditioner, over 100 bars of soap, 30 razors, and over 200 pieces of clothing. Included in that clothing are new socks and underwear. She spent hours on her project organizing, making flyers, and getting donations from businesses, friends, family, and other community members. A big heartfelt thank you from all of us at the Caring Closet. You are an inspiration! Thank you for choosing us for your project for the Girl Scouts of Oregon and Southwest Washington. ❤️

We need your ideas to better support our students!

On October 1, 2019, Superintendent Dr. Rieke-Smith and local leaders are hosting a community input session at Tigard High School in the commons. You are invited to join in. The session is intended to hear about your needs, hopes, requests, and offers.

This is also an opportunity to learn more about Oregon’s Student Success Act – a new law that provides a historic opportunity for our students, your family, and our educators. We really need your input on how best to support student success.

Please go to the following link to confirm your attendance, childcare and language interpretation needs:
https://www.ttsdschools.org//cms/module/selectsurvey/TakeSurvey.aspx?SurveyID=105

Sept 8 to Sept 14 is National Suicide Prevention Week, have a #RealConvo about mental health! Whether that means active listening, talking through it, or just being with someone, all are equally important.

It’s time to shift the culture and have an open and honest conversation about #mentalhealth. Have you had a #RealConvo today?

If you’re unsure of how to reach out to a friend that’s struggling, here are some quick pointers you can use for having a #RealConvo: https://afsp.org/how-to-start-and-continue-a-conversation-about-mental-health-a-realconvo-guide-from-afsp

post_text:
On Wednesday, August 7, 2019, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) will conduct a national emergency alert test through radio, broadcast television, and cable television.

The test will start at 11:20 a.m.(2:20 p.m. EDT) and will last for about a minute.

Please do not call 9-1-1 in response to this test.

For more information visit: https://www.fema.gov/emergency-alert-test

FEMA is conducting this test across the country to ensure that public safety officials have the methods and systems that will deliver urgent alerts and warnings to the public in times of an emergency or disaster. Unlike in prior years, the intent of this year’s test is to evaluate the readiness of the national alerting capability in the absence of internet connectivity so no emergency text messages will be sent.
